\"committee_johnson\">{{cite web |URL=https://cfrsearch.nictusa.com/committees/517449 |title=Michigan Committee Statement of Organization |publisher=[[Michigan Secretary of State]] |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> (born December 2, 1990) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]].\n\nOutside of his political career, Johnson is a deacon at Wayland Christian Reformed Church.<ref name=\"house_johnson\">{{cite web |URL=http://gophouse.org/representatives/westmi/johnson/ |title=Steven Johnson's Bio |publisher=gophouse.org |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gophouse.org/representatives/westmi/johnson/ Steve Johnson at gophouse.org]\n* [https://ballotpedia.org/Steven_Johnson_(Michigan) Steve Johnson at ballotpedia.org]\n* [https://justfacts.votesmart.org/candidate/biography/170519/steve-johnson Steve Johnson at votesmart.org]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title= [[Michigan House of Representatives|Michigan Representatives]]<br>72nd District | before= [[Ken Yonker]]| | after=Incumbent| years=2017\u2013present }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Michigan House of Representatives}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Steven B.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Community College of the Air Force alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberty University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Michigan House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Michigan Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n{{Michigan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "24.247.137.245", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Johnson_(Michigan_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Software Guard Extensions", "text_new": "'''Intel Software Guard Extensions''' ('''SGX''') is a set of [[computer security|security-related]] [[instruction code]]s that are built into some modern [[Intel]] [[central processing unit]]s (CPUs). They allow [[user-level]] as well as [[operating system]] code to define private regions of memory, called ''enclaves'', whose contents are protected and unable to be either read or saved by any process outside the enclave itself, including processes running at higher [[privilege level]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/blogs/2013/09/26/protecting-application-secrets-with-intel-sgx |title=Intel SGX for Dummies (Intel SGX Design Objectives) |website=intel.com |date=2013-09-26}}</ref> SGX is disabled by default and must be opted in to by the user through their motherboard settings on a supported system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/properly-detecting-intel-software-guard-extensions-in-your-applications|title=Properly Detecting Intel\u00ae Software Guard Extensions (Intel\u00ae SGX) in Your Applications|last=johnm|date=2017-08-08|website=software.intel.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\nSGX involves [[encryption]] by the CPU of a portion of memory. The enclave is decrypted [[on the fly]] only within the CPU itself, and even then, only for code and data running from within the enclave itself.<ref name=sd>{{cite web|url=https://it.slashdot.org/story/19/02/12/222254/researchers-use-intel-sgx-to-put-malware-beyond-the-reach-of-antivirus-software?sbsrc=developers|title=Researchers Use Intel SGX To Put Malware Beyond the Reach of Antivirus Software - Slashdot|website=it.slashdot.org}}</ref> The processor thus protects the code from being \"spied on\" or examined by other code.<ref name=sd/> The code and data in the enclave utilize a [[threat model]] in which the enclave is trusted but no process outside it can be trusted (including the [[operating system]] itself and any [[hypervisor]]), and therefore all of these are treated as potentially hostile. The enclave contents are unable to be read by any code outside the enclave, other than in its encrypted form.<ref name=sd/>. Applications running inside of SGX must be written to be side channel resistant as SGX does not protect against side channel measurement or observation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/intel-sgx-and-side-channels |title=Intel SGX and Side-Channels|website=intel.com |date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nSGX is designed to be useful for implementing secure [[remote computing|remote computation]], secure [[web browsing]], and [[digital rights management]] (DRM).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/sgx/details |title=Intel SGX Details |website=intel.com |date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Other applications include concealment of [[Proprietary software|proprietary algorithms]] and of [[encryption key]]s.<ref name=sd/>\n\n==Details==\nSGX was first introduced in 2015 with the sixth generation [[Intel Core]] microprocessors based on the [[Skylake (microarchitecture)|Skylake]] [[microarchitecture]].\n\nSupport for SGX in the CPU is indicated in [[CPUID]] \"Structured Extended feature Leaf\", EBX bit 02,<ref>[https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/07/b7/319433-023.pdf#page=36 Intel Architecture Instruction Set Extensions Programming Reference], Intel, AUGUST 2015, page 36 \"Structured Extended feature Leaf EAX=07h, EBX Bit 02: SGX\"</ref> but its availability to applications requires [[BIOS]]/[[Unified Extensible Firmware Interface|UEFI]] support and opt-in enabling which is not reflected in CPUID bits. This complicates the feature detection logic for applications.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/properly-detecting-intel-software-guard-extensions-in-your-applications|title=Properly Detecting Intel Software Guard Extensions in Your Applications |website=intel.com |date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nEmulation of SGX was added to an experimental version of the [[QEMU]] system emulator in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tc.gtisc.gatech.edu/bss/2014/l/final/pjain43.pdf |title=Intel SGX Emulation using QEMU |website=tc.gtisc.gatech.edu |accessdate=2018-11-02 }}</ref> In 2015, researchers at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] released an open-source simulator named \"OpenSGX\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://github.com/sslab-gatech/opensgx |title=sslab-gatech/opensgx |website=[[GitHub]] |access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\nOne example of SGX used in security was a demo application from [[wolfSSL]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wolfssl.com/wolfssl-at-idf/ |title=wolfSSL At IDF |website=wolfssl |date=2016-08-11}}</ref> using it for cryptography algorithms.\n\nIntel [[Goldmont Plus]] (Gemini Lake) microarchitecture will also add support for Intel SGX.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n== Attacks ==\n\n===Prime+Probe attack===\nOn 27 March 2017 researchers at Austria's [[Graz University of Technology]] developed a proof-of-concept that can grab [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] keys from SGX enclaves running on the same system within five minutes by using certain CPU instructions in lieu of a fine-grained timer to exploit [[Cache memory|cache]] [[DRAM]] side-channels.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chirgwin |first1=Richard |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/03/07/eggheads_slip_a_note_under_intels_door_sgx_can_leak_crypto_keys/ |title=Boffins show Intel's SGX can leak crypto keys |accessdate=1 May 2017 |publisher=The Register |date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite arxiv |eprint=1702.08719|last1=Schwarz|first1=Michael|title=Malware Guard Extension: Using SGX to Conceal Cache Attacks|last2=Weiser|first2=Samuel|last3=Gruss|first3=Daniel|last4=Maurice|first4=Cl\u00e9mentine|last5=Mangard|first5=Stefan|class=cs.CR|year=2017}}</ref>  One countermeasure for this type of attack was presented and published by Daniel Gruss et al. at the [[USENIX]] Security Symposium in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conference/usenixsecurity17/sec17-gruss.pdf |title=Strong and Efficient Cache Side-Channel Protection using Hardware Transactional Memory |date=2017-08-16 |website=USENIX }}</ref> Among other published countermeasures, one countermeasure to this type of attack was published on September 28, 2017, a compiler-based tool, DR.SGX,<ref>{{cite arXiv |title=DR.SGX: Hardening SGX Enclaves against Cache Attacks with Data Location Randomization |date=2017-09-28 |eprint = 1709.09917|last1 = Brasser|first1 = Ferdinand|last2= Capkun|first2= Srdjan|last3= Dmitrienko|first3= Alexandra|last4= Frassetto|first4= Tommaso|last5= Kostiainen|first5= Kari|last6= M\u00fcller|first6= Urs|last7= Sadeghi|first7= Ahmad-Reza|class= cs.CR}}</ref> that claims to have superior performance with the elimination of the implementation complexity of other proposed solutions.\n\n===Spectre-like attack===\n{{main|Spectre (security vulnerability)}}\nThe LSDS group at Imperial College London showed a proof of concept that the [[Spectre (security vulnerability)|Spectre]] speculative execution security vulnerability can be adapted to attack the secure enclave.<ref>{{cite |title=Sample code demonstrating a Spectre-like attack against an Intel SGX enclave.| url=https://github.com/lsds/spectre-attack-sgx}}</ref>  The [[Foreshadow (security vulnerability)|Foreshadow]] attack, disclosed in August 2018, combines speculative execution and buffer overflow to bypass the SGX.<ref>{{cite web|author=Peter Bright - Jul 10, 2018 9:00 pm UTC |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/07/new-spectre-like-attack-uses-speculative-execution-to-overflow-buffers/ |title=New Spectre-like attack uses speculative execution to overflow buffers |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2018-07-10 |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Enclave attack ===\nOn 8 February 2019, researchers at Austria's [[Graz University of Technology]] published findings, which showed that in some cases it is possible to run malicious code from within the enclave itself.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Schwarz|first=Michael|last2=Weiser|first2=Samuel|last3=Gruss|first3=Daniel|date=2019-02-08|title=Practical Enclave Malware with Intel SGX|eprint=1902.03256|class=cs.CR}}</ref> The exploit involves scanning through process memory, in order to reconstruct a payload, which can then run code on the system. The paper claims that due to the confidential and protected nature of the enclave, it is impossible for [[Antivirus software]] to detect and remove malware residing within it. However, since modern anti-malware and antivirus solutions monitor system calls, and the interaction of the application with the operating system, it should be possible to identify malicious enclaves by their behavior, and this issue is unlikely to be a concern for state-of-the-art antiviruses. Intel issued a statement, stating that this attack was outside the threat model of SGX, that they cannot guarantee that code run by the user comes from trusted sources, and urged consumers to only run trusted code.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/02/researchers-use-intel-sgx-to-put-malware-beyond-the-reach-of-antivirus-software/|title=Researchers use Intel SGX to put malware beyond the reach of antivirus software|last=Bright|first=Peter|date=2019-02-12|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n=== MicroScope replay attack ===\nThere is a proliferation of [[Side-channel attack]] plaguing modern computer architecture. Many of these attacks measure slight, nondeterministic variations in the execution of some code, so the attacker needs many, possibly tens of thousands, of measurements to learn secrets. However, the Microscope attack allows a malicious OS to replay code an arbitrary number of times regardless of the programs actual structure, enabling dozens of side-channel attacks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skarlatos|first=Dimitrios|last2=Yan|first2=Mengjia|last3=Gopireddy|first3=Bhargava|last4=Sprabery|first4=Read|last5=Torrellas|first5=Josep|last6=Fletcher|first6=Christopher W.|date=2019|title=MicroScope: enabling microarchitectural replay attacks|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=3307650.3322228|journal=Proceedings of the 46th International Symposium on Computer Architecture  - ISCA '19|language=en|location=Phoenix, Arizona|publisher=ACM Press|pages=318\u2013331|doi=10.1145/3307650.3322228|isbn=978-1-4503-6669-4}}</ref>\n\n=== Plundervolt ===\nSecurity researchers were able to inject timing specific faults into execution within the enclave,\nresulting in leakage of information.  The attack ''can'' be executed remotely, but requires\naccess to the privileged control of the processor's voltage and frequency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rambus.com/blogs/plundervolt-steals-keys-from-cryptographic-algorithms/|title=Plundervolt steals keys from cryptographic algorithms|date=2019-12-11|website=Rambus Blog|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== LVI ===\n{{Main|Load value injection}}\nLoad Value Injection<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lviattack.eu/|title=LVI: Hijacking Transient Execution with Load Value Injection|website=lviattack.eu|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/software-guidance/load-value-injection|title=Load Value Injection|website=software.intel.com|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> injects data into a program aiming to replace the value loaded from memory which is then used for a short time before the mistake is spotted and rolled back, during which LVI controls data and control flow.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Intel MPX]]\n* [[Spectre-NG]]\n*[[Trusted execution environment|Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://software.intel.com/en-us/isa-extensions/intel-sgx Intel Software Guard Extensions (Intel SGX)] / ISA Extensions, Intel\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/48/88/329298-002.pdf Intel Software Guard Extensions (Intel SGX) Programming Reference], Intel, October 2014\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/3e/b9/SF15_ISGC003_81_SGX_DL_100_small.pdf IDF 2015 - Tech Chat: A Primer on Intel Software Guard Extensions], Intel (poster)\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/332680-002.pdf ISCA 2015 tutorial slides for Intel SGX], Intel, June 2015\n*  McKeen, Frank, et al. (Intel), [http://web.cs.wpi.edu/~guttman/cs557_website/papers/trusted_computing/sgx1.pdf Innovative Instructions and Software Model for Isolated Execution ] // Proceedings of the 2nd International Workshop on Hardware and Architectural Support for Security and Privacy. ACM, 2013.\n* [[Joanna Rutkowska]], [http://theinvisiblethings.blogspot.ru/2013/08/thoughts-on-intels-upcoming-software.html Thoughts on Intel's upcoming Software Guard Extensions (Part 1)], August 2013\n* [https://www.virusbtn.com/virusbulletin/archive/2014/01/vb201401-SGX SGX: the good, the bad and the downright ugly] / Shaun Davenport, Richard Ford (Florida Institute of Technology) / Virus Bulletin, 2014-01-07\n*Victor Costan and Srinivas Devadas, [https://eprint.iacr.org/2016/086.pdf Intel SGX Explained], January 2016.\n*[https://github.com/wolfSSL/wolfssl wolfSSL], October 2016.\n* [https://cdn2.hubspot.net/hubfs/1761386/security-of-intelsgx-key-protection-data-privacy-apps.pdf The Security of Intel SGX for Key Protection and Data Privacy Applications] / Professor Yehuda Lindell (Bar Ilan University & Unbound Tech), January 2018\n\n{{Intel}}\n{{CPU technologies|state=collapsed}}\n{{Multimedia extensions}}\n\n[[Category:Intel]]\n[[Category:X86 instructions]]\n[[Category:Computer security]]\n", "text_old": "'''Intel Software Guard Extensions''' ('''SGX''') is a set of [[computer security|security-related]] [[instruction code]]s that are built into some modern [[Intel]] [[central processing unit]]s (CPUs). They allow [[user-level]] as well as [[operating system]] code to define private regions of memory, called ''enclaves'', whose contents are protected and unable to be either read or saved by any process outside the enclave itself, including processes running at higher [[privilege level]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/blogs/2013/09/26/protecting-application-secrets-with-intel-sgx |title=Intel SGX for Dummies (Intel SGX Design Objectives) |website=intel.com |date=2013-09-26}}</ref> SGX is disabled by default and must be opted in to by the user through their motherboard settings on a supported system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/properly-detecting-intel-software-guard-extensions-in-your-applications|title=Properly Detecting Intel\u00ae Software Guard Extensions (Intel\u00ae SGX) in Your Applications|last=johnm|date=2017-08-08|website=software.intel.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\nSGX involves [[encryption]] by the CPU of a portion of memory. The enclave is decrypted [[on the fly]] only within the CPU itself, and even then, only for code and data running from within the enclave itself.<ref name=sd>{{cite web|url=https://it.slashdot.org/story/19/02/12/222254/researchers-use-intel-sgx-to-put-malware-beyond-the-reach-of-antivirus-software?sbsrc=developers|title=Researchers Use Intel SGX To Put Malware Beyond the Reach of Antivirus Software - Slashdot|website=it.slashdot.org}}</ref> The processor thus protects the code from being \"spied on\" or examined by other code.<ref name=sd/> The code and data in the enclave utilize a [[threat model]] in which the enclave is trusted but no process outside it can be trusted (including the [[operating system]] itself and any [[hypervisor]]), and therefore all of these are treated as potentially hostile. The enclave contents are unable to be read by any code outside the enclave, other than in its encrypted form.<ref name=sd/>. Applications running inside of SGX must be written to be side channel resistant as SGX does not protect against side channel measurement or observation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/intel-sgx-and-side-channels |title=Intel SGX and Side-Channels|website=intel.com |date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nSGX is designed to be useful for implementing secure [[remote computing|remote computation]], secure [[web browsing]], and [[digital rights management]] (DRM).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/sgx/details |title=Intel SGX Details |website=intel.com |date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Other applications include concealment of [[Proprietary software|proprietary algorithms]] and of [[encryption key]]s.<ref name=sd/>\n\n==Details==\nSGX was first introduced in 2015 with the sixth generation [[Intel Core]] microprocessors based on the [[Skylake (microarchitecture)|Skylake]] [[microarchitecture]].\n\nSupport for SGX in the CPU is indicated in [[CPUID]] \"Structured Extended feature Leaf\", EBX bit 02,<ref>[https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/07/b7/319433-023.pdf#page=36 Intel Architecture Instruction Set Extensions Programming Reference], Intel, AUGUST 2015, page 36 \"Structured Extended feature Leaf EAX=07h, EBX Bit 02: SGX\"</ref> but its availability to applications requires [[BIOS]]/[[Unified Extensible Firmware Interface|UEFI]] support and opt-in enabling which is not reflected in CPUID bits. This complicates the feature detection logic for applications.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/properly-detecting-intel-software-guard-extensions-in-your-applications|title=Properly Detecting Intel Software Guard Extensions in Your Applications |website=intel.com |date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nEmulation of SGX was added to an experimental version of the [[QEMU]] system emulator in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tc.gtisc.gatech.edu/bss/2014/l/final/pjain43.pdf |title=Intel SGX Emulation using QEMU |website=tc.gtisc.gatech.edu |accessdate=2018-11-02 }}</ref> In 2015, researchers at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] released an open-source simulator named \"OpenSGX\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://github.com/sslab-gatech/opensgx |title=sslab-gatech/opensgx |website=[[GitHub]] |access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\nOne example of SGX used in security was a demo application from [[wolfSSL]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wolfssl.com/wolfssl-at-idf/ |title=wolfSSL At IDF |website=wolfssl |date=2016-08-11}}</ref> using it for cryptography algorithms.\n\nIntel [[Goldmont Plus]] (Gemini Lake) microarchitecture will also add support for Intel SGX.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n== Attacks ==\n\n===Prime+Probe attack===\nOn 27 March 2017 researchers at Austria's [[Graz University of Technology]] developed a proof-of-concept that can grab [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] keys from SGX enclaves running on the same system within five minutes by using certain CPU instructions in lieu of a fine-grained timer to exploit [[Cache memory|cache]] [[DRAM]] side-channels.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chirgwin |first1=Richard |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/03/07/eggheads_slip_a_note_under_intels_door_sgx_can_leak_crypto_keys/ |title=Boffins show Intel's SGX can leak crypto keys |accessdate=1 May 2017 |publisher=The Register |date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite arxiv |eprint=1702.08719|last1=Schwarz|first1=Michael|title=Malware Guard Extension: Using SGX to Conceal Cache Attacks|last2=Weiser|first2=Samuel|last3=Gruss|first3=Daniel|last4=Maurice|first4=Cl\u00e9mentine|last5=Mangard|first5=Stefan|class=cs.CR|year=2017}}</ref>  One countermeasure for this type of attack was presented and published by Daniel Gruss et al. at the [[USENIX]] Security Symposium in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conference/usenixsecurity17/sec17-gruss.pdf |title=Strong and Efficient Cache Side-Channel Protection using Hardware Transactional Memory |date=2017-08-16 |website=USENIX }}</ref> Among other published countermeasures, one countermeasure to this type of attack was published on September 28, 2017, a compiler-based tool, DR.SGX,<ref>{{cite arXiv |title=DR.SGX: Hardening SGX Enclaves against Cache Attacks with Data Location Randomization |date=2017-09-28 |eprint = 1709.09917|last1 = Brasser|first1 = Ferdinand|last2= Capkun|first2= Srdjan|last3= Dmitrienko|first3= Alexandra|last4= Frassetto|first4= Tommaso|last5= Kostiainen|first5= Kari|last6= M\u00fcller|first6= Urs|last7= Sadeghi|first7= Ahmad-Reza|class= cs.CR}}</ref> that claims to have superior performance with the elimination of the implementation complexity of other proposed solutions.\n\n===Spectre-like attack===\n{{main|Spectre (security vulnerability)}}\nThe LSDS group at Imperial College London showed a proof of concept that the [[Spectre (security vulnerability)|Spectre]] speculative execution security vulnerability can be adapted to attack the secure enclave.<ref>{{cite |title=Sample code demonstrating a Spectre-like attack against an Intel SGX enclave.| url=https://github.com/lsds/spectre-attack-sgx}}</ref>  The [[Foreshadow (security vulnerability)|Foreshadow]] attack, disclosed in August 2018, combines speculative execution and buffer overflow to bypass the SGX.<ref>{{cite web|author=Peter Bright - Jul 10, 2018 9:00 pm UTC |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/07/new-spectre-like-attack-uses-speculative-execution-to-overflow-buffers/ |title=New Spectre-like attack uses speculative execution to overflow buffers |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2018-07-10 |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Enclave attack ===\nOn 8 February 2019, researchers at Austria's [[Graz University of Technology]] published findings, which showed that in some cases it is possible to run malicious code from within the enclave itself.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Schwarz|first=Michael|last2=Weiser|first2=Samuel|last3=Gruss|first3=Daniel|date=2019-02-08|title=Practical Enclave Malware with Intel SGX|eprint=1902.03256|class=cs.CR}}</ref> The exploit involves scanning through process memory, in order to reconstruct a payload, which can then run code on the system. The paper claims that due to the confidential and protected nature of the enclave, it is impossible for [[Antivirus software]] to detect and remove malware residing within it. However, since modern anti-malware and antivirus solutions monitor system calls, and the interaction of the application with the operating system, it should be possible to identify malicious enclaves by their behavior, and this issue is unlikely to be a concern for state-of-the-art antiviruses. Intel issued a statement, stating that this attack was outside the threat model of SGX, that they cannot guarantee that code run by the user comes from trusted sources, and urged consumers to only run trusted code.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/02/researchers-use-intel-sgx-to-put-malware-beyond-the-reach-of-antivirus-software/|title=Researchers use Intel SGX to put malware beyond the reach of antivirus software|last=Bright|first=Peter|date=2019-02-12|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n=== MicroScope replay attack ===\nThere is a proliferation of [[Side-channel attack]] plaguing modern computer architecture. Many of these attacks measure slight, nondeterministic variations in the execution of some code, so the attacker needs many, possibly tens of thousands, of measurements to learn secrets. However, the Microscope attack allows a malicious OS to replay code an arbitrary number of times regardless of the programs actual structure, enabling dozens of side-channel attacks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skarlatos|first=Dimitrios|last2=Yan|first2=Mengjia|last3=Gopireddy|first3=Bhargava|last4=Sprabery|first4=Read|last5=Torrellas|first5=Josep|last6=Fletcher|first6=Christopher W.|date=2019|title=MicroScope: enabling microarchitectural replay attacks|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=3307650.3322228|journal=Proceedings of the 46th International Symposium on Computer Architecture  - ISCA '19|language=en|location=Phoenix, Arizona|publisher=ACM Press|pages=318\u2013331|doi=10.1145/3307650.3322228|isbn=978-1-4503-6669-4}}</ref>\n\n=== Plundervolt ===\nSecurity researchers were able to inject timing specific faults into execution within the enclave,\nresulting in leakge of information.  The attack ''can'' be executed remotely, but requires\naccess to the privileged control of the processor's voltage and frequency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rambus.com/blogs/plundervolt-steals-keys-from-cryptographic-algorithms/|title=Plundervolt steals keys from cryptographic algorithms|date=2019-12-11|website=Rambus Blog|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== LVI ===\n{{Main|Load value injection}}\nLoad Value Injection<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lviattack.eu/|title=LVI: Hijacking Transient Execution with Load Value Injection|website=lviattack.eu|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/software-guidance/load-value-injection|title=Load Value Injection|website=software.intel.com|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> injects data into a program aiming to replace the value loaded from memory which is then used for a short time before the mistake is spotted and rolled back, during which LVI controls data and control flow.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Intel MPX]]\n* [[Spectre-NG]]\n*[[Trusted execution environment|Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://software.intel.com/en-us/isa-extensions/intel-sgx Intel Software Guard Extensions (Intel SGX)] / ISA Extensions, Intel\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/48/88/329298-002.pdf Intel Software Guard Extensions (Intel SGX) Programming Reference], Intel, October 2014\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/managed/3e/b9/SF15_ISGC003_81_SGX_DL_100_small.pdf IDF 2015 - Tech Chat: A Primer on Intel Software Guard Extensions], Intel (poster)\n** [https://software.intel.com/sites/default/files/332680-002.pdf ISCA 2015 tutorial slides for Intel SGX], Intel, June 2015\n*  McKeen, Frank, et al. (Intel), [http://web.cs.wpi.edu/~guttman/cs557_website/papers/trusted_computing/sgx1.pdf Innovative Instructions and Software Model for Isolated Execution ] // Proceedings of the 2nd International Workshop on Hardware and Architectural Support for Security and Privacy. ACM, 2013.\n* [[Joanna Rutkowska]], [http://theinvisiblethings.blogspot.ru/2013/08/thoughts-on-intels-upcoming-software.html Thoughts on Intel's upcoming Software Guard Extensions (Part 1)], August 2013\n* [https://www.virusbtn.com/virusbulletin/archive/2014/01/vb201401-SGX SGX: the good, the bad and the downright ugly] / Shaun Davenport, Richard Ford (Florida Institute of Technology) / Virus Bulletin, 2014-01-07\n*Victor Costan and Srinivas Devadas, [https://eprint.iacr.org/2016/086.pdf Intel SGX Explained], January 2016.\n*[https://github.com/wolfSSL/wolfssl wolfSSL], October 2016.\n* [https://cdn2.hubspot.net/hubfs/1761386/security-of-intelsgx-key-protection-data-privacy-apps.pdf The Security of Intel SGX for Key Protection and Data Privacy Applications] / Professor Yehuda Lindell (Bar Ilan University & Unbound Tech), January 2018\n\n{{Intel}}\n{{CPU technologies|state=collapsed}}\n{{Multimedia extensions}}\n\n[[Category:Intel]]\n[[Category:X86 instructions]]\n[[Category:Computer security]]\n", "name_user": "Sta064", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"leakge\" typo fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_Guard_Extensions"}
{"title_page": "Vitaliano Poselli", "text_new": "[[File:Vitaliano Poselli.jpg|thumb|Vitaliano Poselli]]\n'''Vitaliano Poselli''' (1838\u20131918) was an [[Italians|Italian]] architect from [[Sicily]], mostly known for his work in the city of [[Thessaloniki]] in northern [[Greece]].\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in [[Castiglione di Sicilia]] in 1838, and studied in [[Rome]]. In 1867, the [[Catholic Church]] commissioned to him the construction of the Church of Santo Stefano in [[Istanbul|Constantinople]].<ref>[https://books.google.be/books?id=9kNHAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA67 Greece: Modern Architectures in History, by Alexander Tzonis, Alcestis P. Rodi]</ref>\n\nFrom there, the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman government]] sent him to [[Thessaloniki]] (then known as Sel\u00e2nik), where he built some of the most important public edifices of the city. In 1888 he was married and established his residence there. The foreign missions and representatives, such as wealthy merchants of the city, assigned him also the creation of various communal, merchant or private buildings.\n[[File:Poselli, seal.JPG|thumb|Vitaliano Poselli seal on the New Mosque, Thessaloniki]]<ref name=colonas>[https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/media.archnet.org/system/publications/contents/3247/original/DPC0799.pdf Colonas, Vassilis. \"Vitaliano Poselli: An Italian Architecture in Thessaloniki.\u201d] In Environmental Design: Journal of the Islamic Environmental Design Research Centre, 162-171. Rome: Carucci Editore, 1990.</ref>\n\nSome of his most known works are the Idadi\u00e8 Imperial College, today's Philosophy Faculty of the [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|Aristotle University]] (1888), the [[Konak (Thessaloniki)|Government House (''Konak'')]] (1891), the Imperial Army Headquarters, today the Greek [[III Army Corps (Greece)|III Army Corps]] Headquarters, the [[New Mosque (Thessaloniki)|New Mosque]] (1902), the [[Allatini Mills]], the [[Karipeion Melathron]], the State Conservatory building (former Ottoman Bank), the Stoa Malakopi (old ''Banque de Salonique''), the Bank of Athens building (today the [[Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki]]), [[Villa Allatini]] (for the Allatini family, today housing the [[Thessaloniki Prefecture|prefecture]]), Villa Morpurgo/Zardinidi, the [[Immaculate Conception Cathedral, Thessaloniki|Catholic church of the Immaculate Conception]] (1897), the Armenian church (1903) and the Catholic churches, and the synagogue of Bet Saul (1898, destroyed 1943).<ref name=colonas/>\n\nHe had six sons (Primo, Secondo -a musician-, Terzo, Quarto, Quinto and Sesto or Emilio) and two daughters. Singer [[:it:Luisa Poselli|Luisa Poselli]] was his relative.\n\nHe died in 1918 and is buried in the Catholic cemetery of St Vincent in Thessaloniki. Many of his descendants still live in the city.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:AllatiniMills.jpg|[[Allatini Mills]]\nFile:UAT philosophy.jpg|Faculty of Philosophy, [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|AUTH]]\nFile:Ministry-Salonika.jpg|[[Government House (Thessaloniki)|Government House]]\nFile:20121020 exterior of Yeni Mosque Thessaloniki Greece.jpg|[[New Mosque (Thessaloniki)|New Mosque]]\nFile:Karipion.jpg|[[Karipeion Melathron]]\nFile:Stoa Malakopi.jpg|The old ''Banque de Salonique'', often called stock exchange, in Stoa Malakopi\nFile:Jewish museum thessaloniki sign.jpg|[[Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki]]\nFile:Thessaloniki prefecture building.jpg|[[Villa Allatini]]\nFile:Catholic church of the Immaculate Conception, Thessaloniki.JPG|[[Immaculate Conception Cathedral, Thessaloniki|Catholic church of the Immaculate Conception]]\nFile:Armenian Church of Virgin Mary Salonica 2.jpg|Armenian Church of Virgin Mary\nWar Museum of Thessaloniki by Joy of Museums.jpg|[[War Museum of Thessaloniki]]\nFile:Headquarters of the Third Army Corps, Thessalonki.jpg|Army HQs\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Mark Mazower, \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7: \"\u03a0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd\", \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b5\u03be\u03ac\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1, 2006, {{ISBN|960-221-354-X}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poselli, Vitaliano}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Castiglione di Sicilia]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian architects]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Thessalonica]]\n[[Category:Architects from Sicily]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriates in Greece]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Thessaloniki]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Vitaliano Poselli.jpg|thumb|Vitaliano Poselli]]\n'''Vitaliano Poselli''' (1838\u20131918) was an [[Italians|Italian]] architect from [[Sicily]], mostly known for his work in the city of [[Thessaloniki]] in northern [[Greece]].\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in [[Castiglione di Sicilia]] in 1838, and studied in [[Rome]]. In 1867, the [[Catholic Church]] commissioned to him the construction of the Church of Santo Stefano in [[Istanbul|Constantinople]].<ref>[https://books.google.be/books?id=9kNHAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA67 Greece: Modern Architectures in History, by Alexander Tzonis, Alcestis P. Rodi]</ref>\n\nFrom there, the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman government]] sent him to [[Thessaloniki]] (then known as Sel\u00e2nik), where he built some of the most important public edifices of the city. In 1888 he was married and established his residence there. The foreign missions and representatives, such as wealthy merchants of the city, assigned him also the creation of various communal, merchant or private buildings.\n[[File:Poselli, seal.JPG|thumb|Vitaliano Poselli seal on the New Mosque, Thessaloniki]]<ref name=colonas>[https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/media.archnet.org/system/publications/contents/3247/original/DPC0799.pdf Colonas, Vassilis. \"Vitaliano Poselli: An Italian Architecture in Thessaloniki.\u201d] In Environmental Design: Journal of the Islamic Environmental Design Research Centre, 162-171. Rome: Carucci Editore, 1990.</ref> \n\nSome of his most known works are the Idadi\u00e8 Imperial College, today's Philosophy Faculty of the [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|Aristotle University]] (1888), the [[Konak (Thessaloniki)|Government House (''Konak'')]] (1891), the Imperial Army Headquarters, today the Greek [[III Army Corps (Greece)|III Army Corps]] Headquarters, the [[New Mosque (Thessaloniki)|New Mosque]] (1902), the [[Allatini Mills]], the [[Karipeion Melathron]], the State Conservatory building (former Ottoman Bank), the Stoa Malakopi (old ''Banque de Salonique''), the Bank of Athens building (today the [[Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki]]), [[Villa Allatini]] (for the Allatini family, today housing the [[Thessaloniki Prefecture|prefecture]]), Villa Morpurgo/Zardinidi, the [[Immaculate Conception Cathedral, Thessaloniki|Catholic church of the Immaculate Conception]] (1897), the Armenian church (1903) and the Catholic churches, and the synagogue of Bet Saul (1898, destroyed 1943).<ref name=colonas/>\n\nHe had six sons (Primo, Secondo -a musician-, Terzo, Quarto, Quinto and Sesto or Emilio) and two daughters. Singer [[:it:Luisa Poselli|Luisa Poselli]] was his relative.\n\nHe died in 1918 and is buried in the Catholic cemetery of St Vincent in Thessaloniki. Many of his descendants still live in the city.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:AllatiniMills.jpg|[[Allatini Mills]]\nFile:UAT philosophy.jpg|Faculty of Philosophy, [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|AUTH]]\nFile:Ministry-Salonika.jpg|[[Government House (Thessaloniki)|Government House]]\nFile:20121020 exterior of Yeni Mosque Thessaloniki Greece.jpg|[[New Mosque (Thessaloniki)|New Mosque]]\nFile:Karipion.jpg|[[Karipeion Melathron]]\nFile:Stoa Malakopi.jpg|The old ''Banque de Salonique'', often called stock exchange, in Stoa Malakopi\nFile:Jewish museum thessaloniki sign.jpg|[[Jewish Museum of Thessaloniki]]\nFile:Thessaloniki prefecture building.j