{"title_page": "Amy (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 film}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Amy\n| image = Amy (2015 film) poster.png\n| caption = British theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Asif Kapadia]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* [[James Gay-Rees]]\n* George Pank\n* Paul Bell\n}}\n| starring = [[Amy Winehouse]]\n| music = {{plainlist|\n* Amy Winehouse\n* [[Ant\u00f4nio Pinto (composer)|Ant\u00f4nio Pinto]]\n}}\n| cinematography = Matt Curtis\n| editing = Chris King\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* Krishwerkz Entertainment\n* On The Corner Films\n* Playmaker Films\n* [[Universal Music]]\n}}\n| distributor ={{plainlist|\n*[[Altitude Film Distribution]]\n*[[A24 (company)|A24]]\n}}\n| runtime = 128 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 127:43--><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/amy-film |title=''Amy'' (15) |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|2015|05|16|[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2015|07|03|United Kingdom|df=yes}}\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = $3.4 million<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/amy-winehouse-documentary-paints-intimate-portrait-of-singer-1201525287/ |title='Amy': Amy Winehouse Documentary Paints Intimate Picture of Singer |first=Steve |last=Chagollan |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=23 June 2015 |accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>\n| gross = $23.7 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Amy-(2015)#tab=summary | title=Amy (2015) | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Amy''''' is a 2015 British [[documentary film]] about the life and death of British singer-songwriter [[Amy Winehouse]]. The film was directed by [[Asif Kapadia]] and produced by [[James Gay-Rees]], George Pank, and Paul Bell and co-produced by Krishwerkz Entertainment, On The Corner Films, Playmaker Films, and [[Universal Music]], in association with [[Film4 Productions|Film4]]. The film covers Winehouse's life and her struggle with substance abuse, both before and after her career blossomed, and which eventually caused her death.\n\nIn February 2015, a teaser trailer based on the life of Winehouse debuted at the pre-[[Grammy Awards|Grammy]] event in the build-up to the [[2015 Grammy Awards]]. [[David Joseph]], CEO of [[Universal Music Group|Universal Music UK]], announced that the documentary entitled simply ''Amy'' would be released later that year. He further stated: \"About two years ago we decided to make a movie about her\u2014her career and her life. It's a very complicated and tender movie. It tackles lots of things about family and media, fame, addiction, but most importantly, it captures the very heart of what she was about, which is an amazing person and a true musical genius.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/amy-winehouse-documentary-trailer-upcoming-5125655 |title=Amy Winehouse documentary: Trailer for upcoming film debuts at pre-Grammy brunch |first=Simon |last=Keegan |date=8 February 2015 |newspaper=[[The Daily Mirror]] |accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref> The film was shown in the Midnight Screenings section at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/article/61306.html |title=2015 Official Selection |accessdate=16 April 2015 |website=Cannes Film Festival |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418084150/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/article/61306.html |archivedate=18 April 2015  }}</ref> and received its UK premiere at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"HWR\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amy-winehouse-doc-uk-premiere-798261 |date=27 May 2015 |first=Alex |last=Ritman |title=Amy Winehouse Doc 'Amy' Getting U.K. Premiere at Edinburgh Film Festival |accessdate=29 May 2015 |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nThe film was distributed by the [[Altitude Film Distribution]] and [[A24 (company)|A24]], and was released theatrically on 3 July 2015; it received critical acclaim. The film received 33 nominations and won a total of 30 film awards, including for [[European Film Award for Best Documentary|Best European Documentary]] at the [[28th European Film Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35086886 |title=Amy Winehouse documentary wins European Film Award |accessdate=15 December 2015 |website=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> [[BAFTA Award for Best Documentary|Best Documentary]] at the [[69th British Academy Film Awards]], [[Best Music Film]] at the [[58th Grammy Awards]], the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[88th Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"88nom\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscar-nominations-2016-full-list-855670 |title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> and for Best Documentary at the [[2016 MTV Movie Awards]]. The success of the film and the music from [[Amy (soundtrack)|the soundtrack of the same name]] also led Winehouse her second posthumous nomination at the [[2016 BRIT Awards]] for \"British Female Solo Artist\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=Amy Winehouse to battle Adele for 2016 Brit Awards after posthumous nominations |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/amy-winehouse-to-battle-adele-for-2016-brit-awards-after-posthumous-nominations-a6774186.html |first=Adam |last=Sherwin |date=15 December 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317141211/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/amy-winehouse-to-battle-adele-for-2016-brit-awards-after-posthumous-nominations-a6774186.html |archivedate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe film narrative is focused on the life of singer-songwriter [[Amy Winehouse]], who was found dead on 23 July 2011 from [[Alcohol intoxication|alcohol poisoning]], at the [[27 Club|age of 27]] at her home in [[Camden Town|Camden]], North London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14272032 |title=Amy Winehouse post-mortem takes place |website=BBC News Online |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=5 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725170851/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14272032 |archivedate=25 July 2011  }}</ref>\n\nThe film starts with a 1998 home movie depicting a 14-year-old Winehouse singing along with her long-time friend, Juliette Ashby, at the birthday party of their mutual friend, Lauren Gilbert, at a home in [[Southgate, London]]. The rest of the documentary shows the songwriter's life, in a chronological order from her early childhood, to her music career, which attained commercial success through her debut album, ''[[Frank (Amy Winehouse album)|Frank]]'' (2003), and second, final album ''[[Back to Black]]'' (2006), to her troubled relationships, [[self-harm]], [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], the controversial media attention, and her downfall with her drug and alcohol addiction, all until her death in 2011. Winehouse is featured throughout the film talking about her early influences and how she felt about fame, love, depression, family and her music career.\n\n[[File:Amy Winehouse -Virgin Festival, Pimlico, Baltimore, Maryland-4August2007.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The subject of the film, Amy Winehouse performing the Virgin Festival, Pimlico, Baltimore in 2007.]]\nKapadia conducted more than 100 interviews with Winehouse's friends and family that combine to provide a narrative around the star's life and is billed as \"the singer in her own words.\"<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/amy-director-asif-kapadia-on-the-heartbreaking-compelling-film-that-introduces-a-new-side-to-amy-winehouse-10331520.html |title=Amy director Asif Kapadia defends himself against Mitch Winehouse criticisms |date=19 June 2015 |last=Aftab |first=Kaleem |newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The film shows extensive unseen footage and unheard tracks Winehouse had recorded in the years before she died.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/amy-winehouse-documentary-poignant-film-5355870 |title=Amy Winehouse documentary: Poignant film poster revealed as it's given release date |first=Fay |last=Strang |date=18 March 2015 |newspaper=The Daily Mirror}}</ref> Unheard tracks featured in the film are either rare live sessions, such as \"[[Stronger Than Me]]\", \"[[In My Bed (Amy Winehouse song)|In My Bed]]\", \"What Is It About Men?\" and [[Donny Hathaway]]'s \"We're Still Friends\", a cover of [[Johnny Mercer]]'s \"[[Moon River]]\" from when Winehouse attended the [[National Youth Jazz Orchestra]] at the age of 16 in 2000 or never-before heard songs the star wrote, such as \"Detachment\" and \"You Always Hurt The Ones You Love\".\n\nThere are various pieces of extensive, unseen archive footage of Winehouse, such as when she is video-recorded in a cab with friend [[Tyler James (English musician)|Tyler James]] in January 2001 and driving to tours and on her long-term friend, Lauren Gilbert's holiday tape in [[Majorca]], Spain in August 2005. The film also shows various interviews, such as with [[Jonathan Ross]], [[Tim Kash]], and a funny video of when Winehouse is interviewed and talked to about singer [[Dido (singer)|Dido]] in 2004, when she promoted her debut album. The documentary also includes when Winehouse was at the [[50th Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]] in 2008, when she is seen winning the award for \"Record of the Year\".\n\nThe film also features footage from when she was filmed with her ex-husband Blake Fielder-Civil, various performances, and when she auditioned at [[Island Records]] in February 2003, singing \"I Heard Love Is Blind\". Also included is footage from when she was recording her second album in March 2006 and a duet single, \"[[Body and Soul (1930 song)|Body and Soul]]\", with [[Tony Bennett]] in March 2011 as her last recording before her death. Some outtakes are also featured of her last shambolic performance in [[Belgrade]], Serbia, a month before she died. The film concludes with long-term friend Juliette Ashby talking about her last phone call with Winehouse, footage of Winehouse's body being taken out of her home after her death, and Bennett stating: \"Life teaches you really how to live it, if you live long enough.\" It then shows scenes from three days later of footage from Winehouse's funeral at [[Jewish Cemeteries in London|Edgwarebury Cemetery]] and [[Golders Green Crematorium]] in North London. Closing clips end the film with videos of Winehouse from her early years until her death, with [[Ant\u00f4nio Pinto (composer)|Antonio Pinto]]'s composition, \"Amy Forever\".\n\n==Contributors==\nThe following heavily contributed to the documentary through recorded interviews and archive footage:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Amy Winehouse]]\n* Mitchell Winehouse, father\n* Janis Winehouse, mother\n* Raye Cosbert, manager and promoter\n* Nick Shymanksy, ex-manager and friend\n* Blake Fielder-Civil (credited as Blake Fielder), ex-husband\n* [[Tyler James (English musician)|Tyler James]], friend and flatmate\n* Juliette Ashby, friend and flatmate\n* Lauren Gilbert, friend\n* Blake Wood, friend\n* [[Mos Def]] (credited as Yasiin Bey), musician\n* [[Pete Doherty]], musician \n* [[Tony Bennett]], musician\n* [[Mark Ronson]], producer\n* [[Salaam Remi]], producer\n* Andrew Morris, bodyguard\n* Cristina Romete, doctor\n* Chip Somers, drug counsellor \n* Sam Beste, pianist\n* Dale Davis, musical director and bass guitarist \n* Shomari Dilon, sound engineer \n* 'Spiky' Phil Meynell, promoter of Trash Club\n* [[Monte Lipman]], chairman & CEO of [[Republic Records]]\n* [[Lucian Grainge]], head of [[Universal Music Group]]\n* Guy Moot, UK President of [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]\n* Nick Gatfield, president of [[Island Records]]\n* Darcus Beese, A&R of Island Records\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nIn 2012, [[Universal Music]] first approached film producer [[James Gay-Rees]] if the team behind the documentary film about [[Ayrton Senna]] would be interested in creating a project on [[Amy Winehouse]].\n\nOn 25 April 2013, it was announced that the team behind the documentary film ''[[Senna (film)|Senna]]'' (2010), including director [[Asif Kapadia]] and Universal Music, were making a film about the late singer-songwriter [[Amy Winehouse]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Itzkoff |title=Amy Winehouse Documentary Coming From Director of 'Senna' |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/25/amy-winehouse-documentary-coming-from-director-of-senna/ |newspaper=The New York Times |date=25 April 2013 |accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> It was revealed that the film would be very similar to ''Senna'', and that unseen footage of Winehouse would be shown. Kapadia and Gay-Rees stated: \"Everyone fell under her spell. But tragically, Amy seemed to fall apart under the relentless media attention, her troubled relationships, her global success and precarious lifestyle.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/22291812/amy-winehouse-film-to-be-made-by-senna-director |date=25 April 2013 |title=Amy Winehouse film to be made by Senna director |website=BBC [[Newsbeat]]}}</ref> They introduced the project at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]], and it was said the documentary film would be released in 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=24 April 2013 |title=Amy Winehouse Documentary Planned by 'Senna' Director |url= https://variety.com/2013/film/news/amy-winehouse-senna-documentary-1200412204/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe documentary features various unheard tracks Winehouse had completed from when her career began in 2003 until her death. The film includes live sessions, such as: \"[[There Is No Greater Love]]\", \"[[Stronger Than Me]]\", \"[[In My Bed]]\", \"[[Rehab (Amy Winehouse song)|Rehab]]\" and \"What Is It About Men\", covers of [[Johnny Mercer]]'s \"[[Moon River]]\" from when Winehouse was 16 at the National Youth Jazz Orchestra in 2000 and [[Donny Hathaway]]'s \"We're Still Friends\" and never-before heard songs the star wrote, such as \"Detachment\" and the lyrics to \"You Always Hurt The Ones You Love\", combined with Pinto's composition \"Amy Lives\". Winehouse is recorded in March 2006 when she is recording her 2007 single \"[[Back to Black (song)|Back to Black]]\" and there are also cuts and edits of her well-known tracks, which helps unveil every piece of footage in the film.\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Main article|Amy (soundtrack)}}\nOn 8 October 2015, [[Island Records]] announced that the [[Amy (soundtrack)|soundtrack for the film]] would be released on 30 October 2015. The soundtrack includes various tracks that were included in the documentary; including classic tracks from Winehouse and compositions that were featured in the film by composer [[Ant\u00f4nio Pinto (composer)|Antonio Pinto]]. The soundtrack was later released for the second time on vinyl in the United Kingdom and Ireland on 1 April 2016.\n\nThe twenty-three track album includes well-known tracks by Winehouse, such as \"Stronger Than Me\", \"[[Tears Dry on Their Own]]\", and \"Back to Black\", live sessions of \"What Is It About Men\", \"Rehab\", \"We're Still Friends\", and \"[[Love Is a Losing Game]]\", demo tracks; \"Some Unholy War\" and \"Like Smoke\"; a cover of [[The Zutons]]' \"[[Valerie (Mark Ronson song)|Valerie]]\" performed by Winehouse and [[Mark Ronson]] and a 2011 version of \"[[Body and Soul (song)#Tony Bennett and Amy Winehouse version|Body and Soul]]\" performed by Winehouse and [[Tony Bennett]]. The soundtrack is also the second posthumous [[compilation album]] of Winehouse's music.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/08/amy-winehouse-documentary-soundtrack-october-release |title=Soundtrack to Amy Winehouse documentary gets October release |date=8 October 2015 |access-date=29 October 2015 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe commercial success and music behind the film earned Winehouse her second posthumous nomination at the [[2016 BRIT Awards]] for \"British Female Solo Artist\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>, won by singer [[Adele]] and Winehouse posthumously won a [[Grammy Award]] for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Film]]\" at the [[58th Grammy Awards|2016 Grammy Awards]]. This was the ninth indication of Amy's career to this award and the third posthumous.\n\n==Release==\n''Amy'' was released on 3 July 2015 in the United Kingdom, New York, and Los Angeles<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a636166/amy-winehouse-documentary-release-date-confirmed-poster-unveiled.html |title=Amy Winehouse documentary release date confirmed, poster unveiled |first=Simon |last=Reynolds |date=18 March 2015 |website=Digital Spy}}</ref> and worldwide on 10 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/13/amy-winehouse-documentary-gets-us-release-date |title=Amy Winehouse documentary gets U.S. release date |first=Dana Rose |last=Falcone |date=13 May 2015 |website=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref>\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the midnight screenings section at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]] on 16 May 2015.<ref name=\"Cannes\"/> Musicians such as [[Haim (band)|HAIM]], [[Leona Lewis]], and [[Emeli Sand\u00e9]] were in attendance and gathered for the event, as well as the film crew. The film received its UK premiere at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]] in June 2015.<ref name=\"HWR\" />\n\nThe film received a special screening in cinemas around the United Kingdom on 30 June, which was broadcast live from the London GALA Premiere at the [[Picturehouse Cinemas|Picturehouse]]. The screening provided questions from the public on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and from the audience. The film director [[Asif Kapadia]], producer [[James Gay-Rees]], and friend Nick Shymansky answered them and concluded with a tribute to Winehouse with her 2007 music video \"[[Love Is a Losing Game]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Levine |first=Nick |website=[[NME]] |date=17 June 2015 |url=http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/london-premiere-of-amy-winehouse-documentary-to-be/381082 |title=London premiere of Amy Winehouse documentary to be screened live at cinemas nationwide (Special preview screenings will be taking place across the UK on Tuesday, June 30)}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nOn 8 February 2015, a [[Trailer (promotion)|teaser trailer]] of ''Amy'' debuted at the pre-Grammy event in the build-up to the [[2015 Grammy Awards]]. A teaser theatrical poster for the documentary film was released on 18 March 2015 on [[Twitter]], and the first trailer was released on 2 April 2015, with receiving more than two million views [[Altitude Film Distribution|Altitude Film]]'s channel on [[YouTube]]. Footage from the teaser trailer shows Winehouse as a young woman at the beginning of her music career answering questions about how she sees herself as an artist and how she felt about fame.\n\nVarious official teaser clips from the film were released on [[YouTube]] to the buildup and throughout the documentary's release in July by Altitude Film and [[A24 (company)|A24]], including clips of Winehouse talking about how she felt about [[Depression (mood)|depression]], how she thinks she would have handled fame from her early years, when she was recording her album ''[[Back to Black]]'' with her record producer [[Mark Ronson]] in March 2006 and when she was videotaped singing the \"Happy Birthday\" song at the fourteenth birthday party of her friend, Lauren Gilbert, in 1998 which received over one million views after 48 hours. In May 2015, the first teaser clip from the film was released. The short clip features a candid moment of Winehouse messing around with the camera and singing, while Nick Shymanksy, a member of her management team, recalls the beginning of her songwriting process; the video concludes with an unheard track Winehouse had recorded, \"Detachment\", which was arranged to be on her album ''[[Back To Black]]'' (2006).<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/watch-first-official-clip-from-amy-winehouse-documentary-20150508 |title=Watch First Official Clip From Amy Winehouse Documentary |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |date=8 May 2015 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2015, the official theatrical poster was released on the film's Twitter page.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/amy-gets-a-release-date-20150513 |title=Heartbreaking Amy Winehouse Doc 'Amy' Gets Release Date |last=Lattanzio |first=Ryan |date=18 May 2015 |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=22 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517022216/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/amy-gets-a-release-date-20150513 |archive-date=17 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 20 May 2015, the first official full-length trailer was released by Altitude Film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2015/05/20/amy-winehouse-movie-trailer/ |title=Watch the Solemn Trailer for the New Amy Winehouse Documentary |first=Mike |last=Ayers |date=20 May 2015 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> The trailer features the song \"[[Back to Black (song)|Back To Black]]\", which was released in 2007. The video shows footage of Winehouse from her childhood to her early interviews, the rigorous media attention from the paparazzi, performances, various award winnings, her troubled relationship with her husband Blake Fielder-Civil and her statement of how she felt about him: \"I fell in love with someone I would die for\". The trailer also contains voices from people Winehouse knew and how they felt about her, such as [[Tony Bennett]] and [[Mos Def]]. The video concludes with \"[[Love Is a Losing Game]]\" with footage of Winehouse, various five star reviews, and Winehouse saying: \"I don't think I'm going to be at all famous\", and, \"I'm not a girl trying to be a star... I'm just a girl that sings\". The trailer received more than one million views after 24 hours on A24's channel on YouTube. After the film's release, a second official trailer was released that captures the controversial fame of Winehouse's celebrity lifestyle and how she struggled with it throughout her career. On 16 September 2015, another unseen clip was released of Winehouse videoed messing around with friend Nicky Shymansky in [[New York City]] in 2004, after the release of ''[[Frank (Amy Winehouse album)|Frank]]'' (2003).\n\n===Home media===\nOn 16 September 2015, it was announced by [[Universal Music]] that ''Amy'' would be released on [[DVD]]/[[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] and [[Digital distribution|digital download]] on 2 November 2015 in the United Kingdom and Ireland. It was released in the United States on 1 December 2015. The two-disc package includes the film feature along with special features; such as a selection of previously unseen footage of Winehouse, as well as rare performances at Metropolis Studios, the film trailers and the making of the documentary. In November 2015, a special box set limited edition of ''Amy'' was released only in France, that provides the film feature, as well as a special booklet, the film poster, a selection of Amy Winehouse photographs and a T-shirt themed on the film.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Amy'' has broken the UK box office record for the highest opening weekend of a British documentary film, grossing at \u00a3519,000 from 133 cinemas three days after its release on 3 July. It also enjoyed success in the US, earning \u00a3142,000 from just six cinemas before it expanded in the following weeks. The film scored a $37,002 site average in the US in three days. The film opened with $222,015 across six sites, with a location average of $37,002 \u2013 $10,000 more than ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]'' (2004) managed on its first weekend and even beating ''[[March of the Penguins]]'' (2005) {{'}}s $44,373 and the film has increased its box office peak after its initial release nationally on 10 July.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/06/amy-winehouse-documentary-breaks-records-box-office |title=Amy Winehouse documentary breaks box office records |first=Catherine |last=Shoard |date=6 July 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n===Critical response===\n''Amy'' received critical acclaim. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 95% rating based on 213 reviews, with an average rating of 8.36/10. The site's consensus reads, \"As riveting as it is sad, ''Amy'' is a powerfully honest look at the twisted relationship between art and celebrity\u2014and the lethal spiral of addiction.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/amy_2015/ |title=Amy |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=14 February 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports an 85 out of 100 rating based on 41 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/amy-2015 |title=Amy |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Robbie Collin]] from ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' rated the film as four out of five stars and praised the fact that \"Amy Winehouse's glorious rise and heartbreaking fall is movingly documented by the director of ''[[Senna (film)|Senna]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/amy/review/ |title=Amy review: 'piercingly sad'  |first=Robbie |last=Collin |date=8 January 2016 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Guy Lodge from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated that: \"The rise and devastating fall of the gifted British soul singer is chronicled in this deeply felt doc from 'Senna' director Asif Kapadia.\"<ref name=\"Guy Lodge\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/amy-review-cannes-amy-winehouse-documentary-1201493207/ |title='Amy' Review: Intimacy and Intelligence Make Amy Winehouse Doc a Hit |first=Guy |last=Lodge |date=16 May 2015 |magazine=Variety}}</ref> ''[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]]'' and ''[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]'' both also rated the film five out of five, describing the film as \"brilliant\" and \"unmissable\". [[Peter Bradshaw]] from ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film five out of five, describing it as \"a tragic masterpiece\", and saying, \"This documentary about the late British soul singer is an overwhelmingly sad, intimate\u2014and dismaying\u2014study of a woman whose talent and charisma helped turn her into a target\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/16/amy-review-asif-kapadias-amy-winehouse-film-is-a-tragic-masterpiece |title=Amy review: Asif Kapadia's Amy Winehouse film is a tragic masterpiece |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 May 2015}}</ref> Geoffrey Macnab from ''[[The Independent]]'' also rated the documentary five out of five, reviewed it as \"brilliant\" and \"unutterably sad\", and stated: \"There were many, many contributory factors to Amy Winehouse going off the rails, which are explored in the effect of ''Amy''\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/amy-cannes-film-review-brilliant-unutterably-sad-film-depicts-the-descent-of-amy-winehouse-10241679.html |title=Amy, Cannes film review: Brilliant, unutterably sad film depicts the descent of Amy Winehouse |first=Geoffrey |last=Macnab |date=16 May 2015 |newspaper=The Independent |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414225200/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/amy-cannes-film-review-brilliant-unutterably-sad-film-depicts-the-descent-of-amy-winehouse-10241679.html |archivedate=14 April 2016}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', ''Amy'' has been placed at no. 3 out of \"The 50 Best Films of 2015 in Australia\" at the end of the year<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/dec/15/the-50-best-films-of-2015-in-australia-no-3-amy |title=The 50 best films of 2015 in Australia: No 3 \u2013 Amy |first=Henry |last=Barnes |date=15 December 2015 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> and has been placed at no. 6 out of \"The 50 Best 2015  Films in the UK\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/dec/11/the-50-best-films-of-2015-in-the-uk-no-6-amy |title=The 50 best films of 2015 in the UK: No 6 \u2013 Amy |first=Henry |last=Barnes |date=15 December 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Family's response===\nThe film has been heavily criticised by Winehouse's father, Mitch Winehouse. He has distanced himself from the documentary, stating the film is \"misleading\" and \"contains some basic untruths\", according to his spokesman.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/apr/27/amy-winehouse-documentary-family-cannes-film-festival |title=Amy Winehouse documentary is 'misleading', says family |date=27 April 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> On 7 May 2015, Winehouse's father Mitch appeared on ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' and described the film as \"preposterous\". He further stated:\n\n<blockquote>\"The film is representing me in a not very good way. There is no balance, there's nothing about the [[Amy Winehouse Foundation|foundation]]. It's portraying me and Amy in not a very good light.\"<ref name=\"itv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/thismorning/showbiz/mitch-winehouse-on-amy-the-girl-behind-the-name-film |title=Mitch Winehouse upset and angry at Amy film |date=7 May 2015 |website=ITV.com |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, he also said that the film contains \"superb\" and \"beautiful\" footage of Winehouse. He then added: \"Half of me wants to say don't go see it.  But then the other part of me is saying maybe go see the videos, put your headphones in and listen to Amy's music while they're watching the videos.  It's the narrative that's the problem.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/amy-winehouses-father-mitch-winehouse-5652185 |title=Amy Winehouse's father Mitch Winehouse tells fans NOT to go see biopic made about her life |first=Natalie |last=Corner |date=7 May 2015 |newspaper=The Daily Mirror}}</ref>\n\n[[Universal Music]] instigated the documentary but they only secured the cooperation of the singer's parents, Mitch and Janis Winehouse, when they signed up Kapadia as the director for the film. Winehouse's father, who was a fan of the director's previous documentary film ''[[Senna (film)|Senna]]'' (2010), wanted the same treatment to be given to his late daughter's documentary. However, upon watching the completed film about Winehouse, Mitch was unhappy with how the film portrayed him. Feeling he had been portrayed as the villain, Mitch threatened legal action until limited changes were made to the film. However, he has still publicly condemned the final cut of the film, claiming that Kapadia had an agenda to make him the anti-hero from the start.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n\nMitch requested that he wants the film to be further edited, but the film crew have declined his wish, adding: \"When we were approached to make the film, we came on board with the full backing of the Winehouse family, and we approached the project with total objectivity.\" They said the film reflects findings from around \"100 interviews with people that knew Amy\". On 3 July 2015 (the day ''Amy'' was initially released), the singer's father, Mitch appeared on ''[[Loose Women]]'' to defend his place against the film and announced that himself and Winehouse's former boyfriend, [[Reg Traviss]] are making an alternative film, entitled ''A Letter To Amy'', so it's a \"more accurate\" project, to \"correct all the wrongs and omissions\" that were in Kapadia's film.<ref name=\"Mirror\">{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/amy-winehouses-dad-ex-boyfriend-5985040 |title=Amy Winehouse's dad and ex boyfriend want to make their own film of her life |newspaper=The Daily Mirror |date=1 July 2015 |accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> On 24 February 2016, Winehouse's father, Mitch reappeared on ''This Morning'' once again and stated that he would prefer [[Adele]] to win the award that his late daughter was posthumously nominated for at the [[2016 BRIT Awards]].<ref name=\"''Metro\">{{cite news |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/02/24/amy-winehouses-dad-doesnt-want-his-late-daughter-to-win-at-the-brits-5714988/ |title=Amy Winehouse's dad wants Adele to win the BRIT over his late daughter |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |first=Tamara |last=Hardingham-Gill |date=24 February 2016 |accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> This was because the nomination for \"British Female Solo Artist\" was as a result of the film's success, which he seemed to be unhappy about.\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipients and nominees \n! Outcome\n|- \n| [[88th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"88nom\"/>\n| [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]]\n| [[Asif Kapadia]] and [[James Gay-Rees]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[American Cinema Editors#EddieAwards|ACE Eddie Awards]]\n| Best Edited Documentary\n| Chris King\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Austin Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Documentary\n| ''Amy''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Bodil Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Summer of '92 a strong candidate for the Bodil Awards |url=http://cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&l=en&did=303405 |first=Jorn Rossing |last=Jensen |date=11 January 2016 |website=Cineuropa}}</ref>\n|[[Bodil Award for Best Non-American Film|Best Non-US Film]]\n|''Amy''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics]]<ref>{{cite magazine |title='Spotlight' Named Best Film of 2015 by Boston Society of Film Critics |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/spotlight-named-best-film-of-2015-by-boston-society-of-film-critics-1201655050/ |first=Kristopher |last=Tapley |date=6 December 2015 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Documentary Film|Best Documentary Film]]\n| ''Amy''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[2016 BRIT Awards|BRIT Awards]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Amy Winehouse to battle Adele for 2016 Brit Awards after posthumous nominations |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/amy-winehouse-to-battle-adele-for-2016-brit-awards-after-posthumous-nominations-a6774186.html |first=Adam |last=Sherwin |date=15 December 2015 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n| Best British Female Solo Artist\n| [[Amy Winehouse]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[69th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]<ref name=\"BAFTA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35260399 |title=Bafta Film Awards 2016: Winners |accessdate=15 February 2016 |website=BBC News Online}}</ref>\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Documentary|Best Documentary]]\n| ''Amy''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film|Outstanding British Film]]\n| ''Amy''\n| {{nom}}\n|- \n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[British Independent Film Awards]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Lobster on a roll with seven British independent film awards nominations |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/nov/03/the-lobster-british-independent-film-awards-nominations |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n| [[BIFA Award for Best British Independent Film|Best British Independent Film]]\n| ''Amy''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| [[Asif Kapadia]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Documentary\n| Asif Kapadia and [[James Gay-Rees]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Producer of the Year\n| James Gay-Rees\n| {{nom}}\n